narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I feel that I gained a thorough compressive understanding of introductory calculus.
I learned the basics of calculus- limits, derivatives, integrals, etc.

Honestly, I feel like more than anything I learned how to cram information. i think part of this was getting used to the semester style of college education but I truly think i barely learned the material because I usually had one, rarely two classes to understand the material beofre being given extremely challenging PSETs which forced me to simply perform rather than actually process what I was learning. I studied yes, but I really couldn't find time to "cherish" what I was learning because I would fall behind.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: This course could be improved by having more unanimity across the different sections, through the posting of class slides and example problems on the umbrella canvas site. Otherwise, I strongly liked the use of Ximera for learning the material, and the problem sets, while challenging, well prepared me for the exams. Additionally, the peer tutoring sessions were extremely helpful each week. I attended at least 1-2 sessions each week and felt very well prepared for each exam by doing so, and was able to consistently attain high grades on the problem sets.
I think that this course does a good job of cementing the material through the Ximera.

Give peer tutors the correct answers for homeworks; I was led to incorrect answers by them several times which ultimately hindered my understanding of class material. Additionally, make homework more relevant to material taught in class and on Ximera.

Strengths: 
- Good textbook
- clarity of assignments
- great TA hours

Weaknesses:
- Not really "student" friendly? I feel like as a person who asks a lot of questions to full comprehend the class pace was so rapid, I couldn't spend enough time to interrupt when I'm confused
- The PSets are hard. Yes, challenge is necessary but i don't know if 8-10 hours of work (outside of class) is a fair expectation for full time students. Note, this is only Math 112 so I don't think simply shortening the PSets (not lessen the difficulty) will hurt the course, but instead make it more of a class than a part time job.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes. This is a very good introduction to calculus. If you took introductory calculus in high school such as possibly AP Calculus AB, most of the material will be review, but taught in a much more thorough amber than in high school.This class is attainable, but by going to office hours, studying for the exams, and creating through cheat sheets for the exam, good scores are very much attainable.
I would recommend. I took calc in high school which was extremely helpful for this course.
No. I had to almost entirely teach myself all material because the instructor was poorly equipped (not his fault) and the peer tutors were no help either.
No, unless it's a prerequisite for something else.
